tful abusive bastard keeping their kids at home under the guise of homeschooling, so no one sees the bruises. &#10;You could flip your indignation on its head and be thankful that the government is taking an interest in your child's welfare. If that means being visited once a year, so be it. Unfortunately, having 'eyes on the child' means someone's gotta go round your house. &#10;Can I ask what your daughter's social life is like?"/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="729" language="en" documentId="874" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="nega9000" date="06 November 2009 2:42pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6743470" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="874" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="148"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="149" end="413"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="414" end="677"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="678" end="729"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>